&lt;pre&gt;&gt; probably makes sense to start by suggesting a change to 
&lt;a  rel="nofollow" href="https://fetch.spec.whatwg.org/#concept-main-fetch"&gt;https://fetch.spec.whatwg.org/#concept-main-fetch&lt;/a&gt;,
&gt; but the editors there might ask you to write an update to the RFC. &lt;/pre&gt;&lt;pre&gt;

I don't think I understand what change to Fetch would be proposed. The 
section you flagged has two relevant clauses related to HTTPS upgrades:

  5. Upgrade request to a potentially trustworthy URL, if appropriate.
  6. Upgrade a mixed content request to a potentially trustworthy URL, if 
appropriate.

Notably, [*.]localhost is already a potentially trustworthy 
URL: &lt;a  rel="nofollow" href="https://w3c.github.io/webappsec-secure-contexts/#is-origin-trustworthy"&gt;https://w3c.github.io/webappsec-secure-contexts/#is-origin-trustworthy&lt;/a&gt;, 
clause #5.

...which implies to me that the behavior I propose is already what Fetch 
asks for.
